$86k (time and bunkers). During vessel\u2019s first call to Amsterdam charterers requested to load a small portion of denatured ethanol which was to be blended at Immingham, only instruction was this was to be conducted \u201Coutside of EU waters\u201D. Vessel made the transfer but given her location, OPL Immingham, we were in violation of MARPOL regulations forbidding blending at sea. Further she sailed Immingham without the requisite flag dispensations nor exemptions from local authorities to sail without conducting a prewash. A PSC inspection conducted at her second call to Amsterdam resulted in the following 4 deficiencies, listed with the corrective action required:\n\n1.\tblending OPL \u2013 no timeline, corrective action was to obtain the facts about Immingham Port Authority requirements to include in #4 below.\n2.\texemption for prewash not being granted at Immingham \u2013 1 week to obtain exemption  \n3.\tnot properly filling out the cargo record book at Immingham \u2013 1 week to obtain exemption          \n4.\tcorrective action plan for the above due lack of effectiveness this time around \u2013 3 months to update into ISM \n\t \n\tNMM was able to correct #1 by discussion with agents in Immingham who confirmed no prewash facilities and thus no inspectors. #2 and #3 were solved by conducting a prewash at vessel\u2019s upcoming load port and #4 was developed and sent to ISM. NMM superintendent also boarded at Algeciras to conduct internal audit, thus all corrected."},{"modifiedDate":"2022-05-25T19:18:40.473","modifiedByFull":"Fitzgerald, Ethan","remark":"43% fuel surcharge at St. Rose increases port costs $13.5k"},{"modifiedDate":"2022-05-18T17:14:04.64","modifiedByFull":"Fitzgerald, Ethan","remark":"disport rotation added alongwith LS freight \u002B port costs for each"}],"offhireList":[],"tcNumber":null,"tcOutIdEncrypted":null,"tcReletDetail":null}